The paper proposes a novel method for subspace clustering that involves projecting data into a hidden space, calculating globally linear reconstruction coefficients in the kernel space, and truncating trivial coefficients to achieve robustness and block-diagonality. This method is designed to handle large-scale datasets and address the challenge of nonlinear subspace clustering. Given these characteristics, the most likely sub-categories are machine learning (cs.LG), computer vision and pattern recognition (cs.CV), artificial intelligence (cs.AI), data structures and algorithms (cs.DS), and information theory (cs.IT).
